100 Years Ago Today, This is What Was Happening ...

On February 15, 1926, the British Empire's ongoing struggles with labor unrest were highlighted as miners continued their protests against wage cuts, leading to heightened tensions in industrial regions. In the United States, the Senate debated the future of Prohibition, with voices on both sides calling for reform. Meanwhile, in Germany, the political landscape remained tumultuous as the Weimar Republic faced economic challenges, prompting discussions on potential governmental changes.
